    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:97bdc829-f8b3-4cec-be1a-d9d34ad857f9",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is an 8-year-old boy who arrives with his mother after two days of a runny nose, sneezing, mild sore throat, and frequent sniffing. He looks tired but alert, sitting on the exam table swinging his legs and occasionally rubbing at his nose. His voice is slightly nasal, and he has an intermittent dry cough, but he is breathing comfortably and speaking in full sentences. He has a low-grade fever and mild decrease in appetite, though he is still drinking fluids.\n\nAt home, {patientName} is an active third-grade student who enjoys soccer, building with LEGO, and playing video games with his older cousin. He usually sleeps well, though over the last two nights his congestion has made him wake up once or twice. His mother says he has been less energetic than usual but still wants to watch cartoons and play quietly with toy cars. He attends school regularly, where several classmates have recently had colds.\n\n{patientName} lives with his parents and a younger sister in a nonsmoking household. His family is attentive and supportive, and his mother has been encouraging rest, warm soup, and extra water. He has several close friends at school and is generally social and cheerful, though today he is clingier than usual and clearly uncomfortable from nasal congestion.\n\nHe is appropriately dressed for the season, with warm skin, watery nasal discharge, and mild redness of the nasal mucosa and throat. There is no rash, no drooling, and no signs of respiratory distress. Overall he appears like a child with a straightforward upper respiratory viral illness rather than a toxic or severely ill patient."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:6c8fc043-4f1f-4056-8c17-d28917e6f6e4",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is generally healthy with normal growth and development. He has no chronic cardiopulmonary disease and no history of asthma. He has not had recent hospitalizations. His current illness began 2 days ago after exposure to classmates with upper respiratory symptoms. Since then he has had nasal congestion, clear rhinorrhea, sneezing, mild sore throat, dry cough, low-grade fever, and reduced appetite, but no vomiting, ear pain, shortness of breath, chest pain, or lethargy.\n\nHe is up to date on routine childhood immunizations. He drinks fluids well and has maintained normal urine output. There is no tobacco exposure at home. Supportive measures tried so far include honey in warm water, saline steam from a shower, and rest, with partial symptom relief. His mother reports a remote tonsillectomy for recurrent tonsillitis several years ago."
          }
        ]
      }
